observations.recommendation:
We recommended, and Management agreed to require:
The CTO to –
Request transaction history from the AGDB for the identified dormant and closed accounts and prepare the necessary supporting documents to be submitted to CAD to facilitate the required adjustments;
Regularly coordinate with the CAD to ensure that the cashbook balances are reconciled with the SL balances of the CIB accounts maintained by the CAD.  Any discrepancies noted should be communicated to CAD for the preparation of BRS and appropriate book adjustments;
The CAD to –
Assign additional personnel responsible for bank reconciliation to ensure timely and complete submission of BRS for all bank accounts;
Ensure that identified reconciling items in the BRS are immediately adjusted in the books to prevent the accumulation of such and to establish the accuracy and completeness of the CIB accounts;
The CAD and the CTO to –
Strengthen coordination as regards the management of Cash accounts and make representation with the City’s AGDBs to obtain the necessary documentation for dormant and closed accounts, thereby ensuring the fair presentation of financial statements;
Prepare a reconciliation of the discrepancies noted between their records to establish the correct balance of the individual bank accounts, and prepare the necessary adjusting entries supported by complete documentation to ensure accurate presentation of accounts in the Financial Statements; and
Henceforth, ensure compliance with the guidelines set forth under Paragraph 27 of IPSAS 1 and Item 3 of COA Circular No. 96-011.

We recommended, and Management agreed to direct:
The CAD to –
Require the concerned AOs to immediately settle their unliquidated CA through the issuance of demand letters; otherwise, enforce the remedies available to the City in case of non-liquidation;
Refrain from granting additional CA unless the previous CA is first settled or a proper accounting thereof is made.  Moreover, require immediate liquidation and/or assign subsequent grants to other AOs to comply with existing laws, rules, and regulations;
Ensure that the grant of CA to AOs is within the limit of their cash accountability;
Moving forward, strictly adhere to the provisions of PD No. 1445, COA Circular Nos. 97-002, 2012-001, 2018-003, and Treasury Circular 
No. 02-2019.

We recommended and Management agreed to:
Perform periodic reconciliation of the CAD and the hospital records for the transmitted PhilHealth claims, including denied and RTH claims, and those under appeal or refiled to establish the correct balance of the Due from GOCCs - PhilHealth account;
Set up an Allowance for Impairment – Due from GOCCs account for denied and RTH claims, and monitor the subsequent collection or final denials of such and prepare the necessary adjusting entries accordingly;
Ensure compliance with the complete documentation for the processing of reimbursement claims and the timely filing of all hospital claims within the prescribed period with the PhilHealth; and
Henceforth, strictly observe the provisions of Paragraph 27 of 
IPSAS 1, PhilHealth Circular No. 2019-0001, Paragraph 22 of IPSAS 26 and Section 35 of RA No. 10606.

We recommended, and Management agreed to require:
The HCDRD to –
Provide the CAD with complete and updated data/information on all housing projects, including collection records, to ensure accurate and timely financial reporting;
Enhance collection mechanisms to improve arrears recovery and sustain the SHP by:
assessing the financial capacity of the beneficiaries and offering options such as condonation of penalties, account restructuring or discounts for prompt or full payment;
issuing and following up on demand letters for immediate arrears settlement, and coordinating with the CLD for appropriate legal remedies, if warranted;
strengthening awareness campaign and continuous communication with the beneficiaries, emphasizing their obligation under the Contract to Sell or Lease Agreement;
The City Legal Department (CLD) revisit the provisions of the Contract to Sell to align the social responsibility of the City with the enforcement of penalties against those delinquent beneficiaries; and
The CAD to prepare an adjusting entry to correct the misclassified recording of payments and ensure adherence to relevant laws and regulations on fund classification and maintenance of a special fund for rental collections.

We recommended, and Management agreed to require:
The CAD to –
Prepare the necessary adjusting entries to reflect correct balances of IA and their corresponding Accumulated Depreciation, Depreciation Expense, and Government Equity accounts;
Prepare and submit the Lapsing Schedule of all PPEs to validate the correctness of the book value of the assets and the corresponding depreciation expense during the period;
The Inventory Committee to –
Conduct physical inspection and certify the non-existence of the reported demolished IA;
Moving forward, ensure that a complete report of disposal is submitted to CAD for proper derecognition of disposed/demolished PPEs in the books; and
Strictly adhere to Paragraph 27 of IPSAS 1, Paragraphs 66, 71 and 82 of IPSAS 17, Section 194 of COA Circular 92-386 and Section 4.7 of COA Circular No. 2015-008.

We recommended, and Management acted upon on the following:
The Inventory Committee conducts a comprehensive reconciliation between the RPCPPE and accounting records to verify the existence and completeness of PPE balances;
The CGSD ensure that all pertinent documents for demolished assets are adequately prepared and transmitted to CAD for the proper and timely derecognition of these assets;
The CAD to prepare the necessary adjusting entries related to the misclassified BOS to their appropriate accounts; and
Strictly adhere to Paragraph 27 of IPSAS 1, Paragraph 82 of IPSAS 17, COA Circular No. 2020-006, Section 194 of COA Circular No. 92-386, and Item 5, Section 4 of COA Circular No. 2016-006 to ensure accurate financial reporting.

We recommended that Management require:
The CTRC, together with QCED, City Architect Department (CArD) and Parks Development and Administration Department (PDAD), thoroughly review the status of terminated projects to assess their usability, physical condition, and completeness. Consequently, issue a certificate of acceptance if the projects are deemed usable and submit the same to CAD to establish the proper accounting treatment of the subject projects;
The QCED, CArD and PDAD to immediately conduct a detailed inspection and validation of the projects recorded under the CIP account, specifically those without details or undetermined status, to facilitate the completion of the necessary documents for proper identification and subsequent adjustment in their respective PPE account in the books;
The CAD to –
Regularly coordinate with the concerned Departments for the submission of all documents related to the terminated and completed projects to support the preparation of reclassification of these projects to the appropriate PPE accounts, including the provision for depreciation;
Prepare the necessary adjusting entries and update SL balances to correct the erroneous recording and misclassified accounts; and
Strictly adhere to Paragraphs 27 of IPSAS 1, Section 50 of the MNGAS for LGUs, Volume I and COA Circular No. 2015-009.

We recommended, and Management agreed to require the Inventory Committee to:
Accomplish the RPCPPE properly with all the required details in the prescribed format and coordinate with the CAD and other relevant offices to provide the necessary information for any unfilled sections;
Prepare and submit the consolidated RPCPPE based on the result of the conduct of Inventory taking within the prescribed timeframe;
Exclude intangible assets, semi-expendable items, and personal property items in the RPCPPE;
Identify all tangible items that meet the definition and criteria of PPE but cost less than P50,000.00 and shall be accounted for in the books as semi-expendable property, pursuant to COA Circular 
No. 2022-004. Accordingly, make the necessary adjustments to reclassify the previously classified PPE to the appropriate 
semi-expendable property account in accordance with COA Circular No. 2024-006;
Strictly adhere to Section 124, Volume I, and Annex 49 of the MNGAS for LGUs.

We recommended, and Management agreed to direct the MDAD to:
Consider enforcing the Market Rental Rates to further increase revenue and ensure compliance thereon;
Coordinate with the CTO to ensure calibrations of weighing scales are done on a quarterly basis;
Ensure the regular and timely updating of the Price Monitoring Board, based on the suggested Department of Trade and Industry prices, located in the public markets, to provide consumers with fair pricing information;
Immediately coordinate with the responsible Office relative to the requests for repair or replacement of the CCTV cameras that are malfunctioning or not functioning; and
Henceforth, strictly adhere to the provisions of City Ordinance 
No. SP-2459, s. 2015, and its IRR.

We recommended, and Management agreed to require:
The DBO to enhance monitoring procedures by –
Preparing a comprehensive list of BP applications showing details as to issued OPs and Tax Declaration applications to identify those applications with incomplete requirements;
Regularly monitoring completed buildings/structures with BPs and requiring submission of Certificates of Completion for the issuance of OPs and the payment of the required fees and penalties (if any);
Requiring the IAD of the DBO to enforce compliance with CDOs and conduct follow-up actions to ensure adherence to existing guidelines/requirements;
Updating the requirements of the DBO Citizens Charter in alignment with the Ease of Doing Business Act to ensure the timely securing of all necessary permits and the efficient processing of transactions;
The CAO to review the Schedule of Buildings/Structures with OPs submitted by the DBO, and to ensure that all constructions supposed to have been completed are already assessed for local taxation purposes;
The DBO and CAO to coordinate –
to ensure the strict implementation of the rules and regulations on Occupancy Permit and assessment of real property tax;
with HRMD to re-evaluate the need for additional manpower complement to address the challenges faced by the former department; and
Henceforth, strictly comply with the provisions of the existing law, rules and regulations.

We recommended, and Management agreed to:
Distribute any unutilized HEA funds to eligible HCWs and non-HCWs immediately and ensure the efficient and full utilization of HEA funds upon receiving fund transfers from the DOH. Moving forward, in similar cases of voluminous payments, Management should design and implement an efficient payment method to address the distribution of funds and strictly comply with the MOA requirements;
Promptly prepare and submit the required Liquidation Report, together with the required supporting documents, to DOH and COA Auditors;
Facilitate the proper adjustment or refund of over-withheld withholding taxes to the affected beneficiaries and moving forward, ensure that the required and appropriate withholding of taxes are correctly deducted before making any payment to employees/ recipients; and
Henceforth, strictly adhere to the provisions of RA No. 11712, DOH AO No. 2022-0039, DOH –DBM JAO No. 2023-0001 and the MOA to prevent future discrepancies in the distribution of HEA funds.

We recommended, and Management agreed to:
Reassess all non-moving or dormant accounts and ensure that copies of MOA/TAs, Liquidation Reports, Status of Utilization, and other relevant documents related to these fund transfers are available to determine their status of implementation and ensure that fund balances, if any, are properly accounted for and disposed of in accordance with existing COA regulations;
Immediately coordinate with the respective Source Agency/grantor, through the CLD, to obtain copies of MOA/TAs that are unavailable to establish proper accountability for these transactions and submit to COA a complete copy thereof to support balances reported in the Due to NGAs account;
Cause the prompt return of the excess funds from fully utilized fund transfers to the source agencies if explicitly provided for in the MOA/TA, otherwise transfer the excess funds to the GF of the City after proper coordination with the source agencies;
Moving forward, ensure adherence to provisions in COA Circular 
Nos. 94-013, 2016-005, 2023-008, and 2012-001 to ensure comprehensive documentation and proper management of all fund transfers requiring MOAs, TAs, and FURs in the City’s records.

We recommended, and Management agreed to require the CPDD, together with other concerned Departments, to:
Conduct thorough planning and exercise prudence in determining and prioritizing development projects to be funded under the 20% DF, to avoid underutilization and non-implementation of the identified PPAs;
Ensure extensive coordination with the target beneficiaries through public consultations, and thorough site inspections before proceeding with the procurement process to prevent or minimize potential issues that may lead to the suspension or cancellation of priority projects;
Create a monitoring team to regularly review and evaluate the status of fund utilization and accomplishments. Accordingly, coordinate and strategize to optimally utilize the 20% DF; and
Henceforth, strictly observe the guidelines on the appropriation and utilization of the 20% DF, pursuant to Sections 3 and 4 of DBM-DOF-DILG JMC No. 1, s. 2020.

We recommended, and Management agreed to require:
The QCCPC Secretariat, through the CPDD, to –
Designate a permanent staff to prepare the required reports and facilitate coordination among the implementing offices involved in the implementation of the QCCPC programs;
Ensure the timely preparation and submission of the required reports pertaining to the monitoring of physical outputs and accomplishments in accordance with the DILG-MC No. 2021-039, E.O. No. 12, s. 2024, and 2023 BOM for LGUs;
The CPDD to prepare and submit LBAc Form No. 6 or the “Monitoring of Physical Outputs and Accomplishments” as required under the 2023 BOM for LGUs; and
The CBD and CAD to create a sub-office code for the QCCPC fund to ensure proper monitoring and accountability of appropriations, expenditures, and disbursements, to enhance the accuracy and efficiency in tagging, monitoring, and reporting funds that are mainstreamed or attributed to other departments.

We recommended, and Management agreed that:
The CPDD and the CAD reconcile their respective records on obligations and disbursements pertaining to the Senior Citizens Fund to establish a single, reliable source of financial data;
The City conduct capacity-building activities to arm the CPDD and CBD with appropriate tools in the preparation of plans and reports to monitor and assess pertinent PPAs effectively;
The CPDD to prepare and submit the required reports pertaining to the monitoring of physical outputs and accomplishments in accordance with the 2023 BOM for LGUs; and
The CBD and CAD create a Monitoring Tool for the Senior Citizens fund in their respective records to facilitate accurate tagging, monitoring and reporting of appropriations, expenditures, and disbursements.

We recommend, and Management agreed to require:
The CAD, particularly the FAAD and PBRD, to –
Review and analyze the SLs, particularly those with outstanding balances, negative balances and those with erroneous recording of transactions, to determine the correct amount of taxes due for immediate remittance to the BIR. Accordingly, prepare the necessary adjustments to ensure accurate presentation of the account in the financial statements;
Facilitate the prompt remittance/payment of all outstanding taxes as of year-end;
In cases where primary supporting documents can no longer be located, use the secondary records, such as the bank statements, Check Disbursement Journal, Cashbooks and BIR Acknowledgements Receipts, to establish the amounts of unrecorded withheld taxes;
The concerned departments, particularly HRMD and CTO, to ensure timely submission of the supporting documents for withholding and remittance of taxes on employees and suppliers/contractors for proper recording in the books; and
Strictly comply with Paragraph 27 of IPSAS 1, BIR RMO No. 8-2003, Section 2.58 (a) of BIR RR No. 2-98, as amended by BIR RR No. 11-2018 and RMC No. 23-2012.

We recommended, and Management agreed to:
Ensure timely remittance of premium contributions in line with the requirements of the IRR to avoid possible payment of penalties, interests, and fines;
Formally communicate issues and concerns to personnel with personal data correction or update cases to ensure proper notification and expedite compliance;
Immediately trace, locate and recover the related supporting remittance records and reconcile the book balances for the P497,750.00 unreconciled/unsubstantiated Due to PhilHealth. Subsequently, prepare the necessary adjustments in the books;
Collect and duly remit the PhilHealth premium contributions of all directly hired JOs under the Group Enrolment Scheme in compliance with the requirements of PhilHealth Circular No. 2017-0008 dated June 30, 2017; and
Henceforth, strictly observe the requirements of Sections 18(b), Rule III, Title III of the Revised IRR of the National Health Insurance Act, RA No. 7875, as amended by RA No. 9241 and RA No. 10606, Sections 111 and 112 of Presidential Decree 1445, Section 11 of the Revised IRR of the National Health Insurance Act of 2013 and PhilHealth Circular 
No. 2017-0008 dated June 30, 2017.

We recommended and Management agreed to:
Immediately remit all outstanding premium contributions and loan payments withheld from City employees, and ensure full payment within the prescribed period to avoid the imposition of interest and penalties by GSIS;
Conduct a thorough analysis and retrieve supporting documents to establish the final balances of the SLs;
Perform monthly reconciliation between the records of the CAD-FAAD, CAD-PBRD and HRMD to ensure accurate and timely recording and remittance of all withheld amounts to GSIS; and
Strictly adhere to the provisions of RA No. 8291 and Paragraph 27 of IPSAS 1.

We recommended and Management agreed to:
Conduct a detailed reconciliation between the City’s records and 
Pag-IBIG’s database to proactively identify and rectify any discrepancies;
Remit to Pag-IBIG all outstanding premium contributions and loan payments withheld from City employees and within the prescribed period, to avoid potential interest and penalties;
Formally notify the concerned employees to update their Pag-IBIG records, provide clear guidance on the required actions and establish a compliance monitoring system to track employee submissions; and
Strictly comply with Section 3 of Rule VII of Implementing Rules and Regulations of RA No. 9769 to ensure timely and accurate remittance of contributions and loan payments, thereby safeguarding City employees from unnecessary penalties that may be imposed by the HDMF.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive direct the Municipal Accountant and General Services Officer to:
Observe the proper conduct of physical count to come up with a reliable report pursuant to the above cited COA Circular;
Invite Commission on Audit (COA) Representative during the conduct of inventory;
Prepare and submit approved Physical Inventory Plan to the COA Audit Team at least ten (10) calendar days before the scheduled start of inventory taking activities; and
Undertake the disposal proceedings and derecognize unserviceable properties from the accounting books and property records upon disposal thereof based on the approved Inventory and Inspection Report on Unserviceable Property (IIRUP).

The Inventory Committee to conduct a complete physical inventory of Property, Plant, and Equipment (PPE) and Investment Property. This should include a reconciliation of the physical count with the property and accounting records, as required by Chapter 4 of the Handbook on Property & Supply Management System and Paragraph 4 of Section 114 of the MNGAS for LGUs, Volume I. Any discrepancies should be thoroughly investigated, cleared, and reconciled immediately and written explanations should be obtained from accountable and responsible persons if necessary.
The implementation of the procedures on one time cleansing of PPE accounts is also recommended per COA Circular No. 2020-006 dated January 31, 2020;
The Municipal Accountant and the Municipal General Services Officer to enhance documentation and record-keeping practices related to PPE and Investment Property by preparing and continuously maintaining and updating PPE ledger cards and property cards, respectively. Both offices should ensure that all movements of PPE are properly recorded and documented to facilitate accurate reconciliation and reporting;
The recorded values of constructed School Buildings and procured Sports Equipment reflected in the financial statements which are used/ in custody of the public schools in the Municipality should be transferred to the DepEd Division Office of Nueva Vizcaya thru Deed of Donation and derecognized in the books of the Municipality.
The members of the Inventory Committee to undergo training on property and supply management, if necessary.

We recommended and reiterated to Management the following:

LCE create a committee to investigate the nature, whereabouts and existence of said breeding animals of which the result of the investigation must be submitted for evaluation;
Request authority from COA for the derecognition in the books of the Municipality the recorded values of the breeding animals since the MLGU has no control over these, thus, it should not have been recorded as part of its assets, in the first place, and ownership thereof should have been transferred to the recipients upon the distribution.

We recommended that the Municipal Accountant:
locate available records/documents to determine the source agency and corresponding amount of fund transfers from NGAs of the unknown balances;
reconcile with the Municipal Treasurer for the discrepancies on their records and effect correction for the fair presentation of financial statements;
maintain Subsidiary Ledgers for the Due to NGAs Account; and
comply with the provision of Section 2 and 111 of P.D. No. 1445.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor instruct the Municipal Accountant to:

a. Prepare adjusting entries to properly classify the accounts amounting to P594,113.46;

b. Reconcile the variance of P(513,808.18) with the SA and submit liquidation report or make adjustments in the books of accounts, if necessary;

c. Revert/refund the amount of P33,642.65 to the SA and prepare the necessary reports or documents to close the project in both the IA and SA books; and

d. Extend efforts to communicate with the SA regarding the utilization of non-moving funds amounting to P71,664.91 and prepare necessary adjustments if warranted.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor instruct the:

a. Municipal Accountant to inform in writing the suppliers/contractor concerned of their outstanding claims against the agency;

b. Municipal Treasurer to facilitate the prompt release of the guaranty/security deposits to prevent further accumulation of balances in the liability account.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor:
• Instruct the Municipal Accountant to:
➢ Make necessary adjusting entries to recognize the Semi-Expendable Machinery and Equipment Expenses, and Semi-Expendable Furniture, Fixtures and Books Expenses;
➢ Prepare and maintain the SPLC and submit the same to Audit Team for validation;
➢ Ensure that all acquired and issued tangible items which meet the definition and recognition criteria of PPE but with cost below P50,000.00, were accounted as SEPs in the book of accounts of the Municipality in accordance with Item 3.3 and 4.0 of COA Circular 2024-006;
• Instruct the Property Custodian Designate to:
➢ Prepare and maintain the SPC, RegSPI, RSPI and RPCSP to strengthen control over SEPs, and submit the same to the Audit Team for validation; and
➢ Notify/inform the Audit Team on the schedule of the physical inventory count for SEPs of the Municipality.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor require the:
1. Municipal Accountant to ensure proper cut-off of transactions and recording;
2. Municipal Accountant to maintain the subsidiary ledgers for each collector for
proper monitoring of the collections;
3. Municipal Treasurer to ensure that all RCDs are properly filled out, supported,
and acknowledged;
4. Municipal Treasurer to update her Cashbooks;
5. Municipal Treasurer to present to the Audit Team the updated Cashbooks for
verification;
6. Municipal Treasurer to ensure that her Cashbooks are immediately updated; and
7. Municipal Treasurer to strictly enforce the policy directing all collectors to remit
their collections to the liquidating officer or to the Municipal Treasurer before
the close of each business day.

Also, ensure that the necessary internal controls to strengthen the recordkeeping
and monitoring of collections are designed and implemented, in accordance with
relevant laws, rules, and regulations.

Recommendation:
We recommended to the Municipal Accountant to –
Make the necessary adjusting entries to transfer the balances of QHCI professional fees from the account “Other Payables” to “Trust Liabilities” in the Trust Fund books of accounts, supported with the necessary documents and submit to the audit team for verification;
Transfer the “Other Payables” for professional fees recorded in the General Fund books of accounts to “Trust Liabilities” in the Trust Fund books of accounts, supported with the necessary documents and submit to the audit team for verification, the corresponding bank account be classified also as one of the bank accounts of the Trust Fund;
Classify the bank account for Lying-in HCI charges as one of the bank accounts of the General Fund;
Trace the reason for the difference of P71,818.25 and make the necessary journal entries to correct the affected accounts, the Journal Entry Voucher to be supported with working papers and to be submitted to the audit team for verification;
Subsequently, record receipts for Professional Fees as “Trust Liabilities” in the Trust Fund books of accounts

Recommendation:
We recommended the following -
The Management to –
Ensure that the project name and property name are clearly identified in the budget, as these names are used in the preparation of related documents submitted to the OMA which is used in recording the transaction in the books of accounts of the LGU;
For big infrastructure projects, identify if a phase to be implemented is capable of operations to avoid naming it by phase so that it may be recorded as a separate property.
The Municipal Engineer to ensure that the specific property is identified in the Program of Works in order that the expenditure may form part of the carrying amount of the property;
The Municipal Planning and Development Office to submit report of completed and operational projects for the year to the OMA to facilitate the transfer of CIP to the proper asset account.
The Municipal Accountant to –
Apply a change in accounting estimates when there is a capitalizable expenditure related to the property to ensure that depreciation expenses are correctly recognized in the Statement of Financial Performance of the LGU;
Review the Program of Works to determine if it includes demolition so that the cost associated with the demolished or dismantled section can be properly derecognized;
Ensure that only completed and operational projects are recorded in the appropriate asset accounts.
Ensure that a project or property is properly recorded in its correct PPE account.
Ensure that each property of the LGU has a dedicated subsidiary ledger, and record all capitalizable expenditures related to that property in its respective subsidiary ledger.

Recommendation:
We recommended to the Management to request for derecognition or write-off of dormant accounts by following strictly the guidelines and procedures prescribed in COA Circular No. 2023-008;
Henceforth, the Municipal Accountant to –
Exert effort to retrieve documents for the unidentifiable balance of the disallowances and charges and continue issuing demand letters for the payment thereof;
Ensure that the current transactions and those below 10 years for receivables, cash advances, and fund transfers are properly documented and appropriately acted upon immediately to avoid being dormant. If the AO fail to settle his/her accountabilities despite the demand, the action could either be salary deduction or filing of appropriate cases;
Send demand letters and exhaust collection remedies for receivables under 10 years  to prevent dormancy;
Disclose comparative information in the Notes to Financial Statements relative to the dormant accounts;
Prepare the Schedules of Dormant Accounts (SDA) Quarterly to submitted to the COA Office on or before the 15th day of the ensuing month.

Recommendation:
We recommended the following  –
The Municipal Budget Officer to ensure correct expense classification for projects during the budgeting process, as misclassification often leads to errors in recording the transactions in the books of accounts of the LGU;
The Municipal Planning and Development Office, together with the Project Monitoring Committee to –
Coordinate with the Supply and Property Management Division for recording in the property cards and for inventory tagging of the completed project;
Submit to the OMA a duly signed and approved report on the projects that are completed and operational during the year, indicating the name of the project, quantity, its unit cost, and inventory number;
The Office of the Municipal Accountant to –
Maintain individual subsidiary ledger for each cottage of the LGU’s Lowan-Lowan Spring and Swimming Resort Cottages and record any subsequent capitalizable cost relating to the said cottages to its corresponding SL;
Make the necessary adjusting journal entries to correct the recording of the disbursements for the Rehabilitation of Lowan-Lowan Spring and Swimming Resort Cottages in the total amount of P1,097,088.73, photocopies of the journal entry voucher and its supporting documents be submitted to the audit team;
Utilize the duly signed and approved report from the MPDO along with the Certificates of Completion to accurately record the completed project in its appropriate asset account.

Recommendation:
We recommended the following:
Municipal Accountant to –
Coordinate with the Provincial Government of Bukidnon to reconcile the discrepancies in the balance of fund transfers between the records of OMA and the PGB’s books of accounts;
Make the necessary adjusting journal entries to correct the balance of the “Due to LGUs”  and “Property, Plant, and Equipment” accounts in the Trust Fund books of accounts by following the journal entries shown above, photocopies of the journal entry voucher (JEV) and its supporting documents be submitted to the audit team;
The properties listed in Annex M be recorded only in the General Fund books of accounts of the Municipality and the Barangays upon receipt of the Deed of Donations from the Provincial Government of Bukidnon;
Meanwhile, the OMA to disclose in the Notes to Financial Statement of the Municipality and the affected barangays the properties that they are already using but not yet recorded in the books of accounts of the Municipality and the Barangays pending the receipt of Deed of Donations.
The Management to –
Follow-up the Deed of Donation from the Provincial Government of Bukidnon;
Once the Deed of Donation was obtained, forward a copy to the Office of the Municipal Accountant for the recording of the assets in the General Fund books of accounts of the Municipality.

Recommendation:
We recommended the following  –
The Management to
Submit necessary documents to prove that the change in the annual budget, that is “Installation of Street Lighting System at Poblacion and San Jose” to “Installation of LED Lights along Municipal Road – Poblacion” was authorized by the Sangguniang Bayan of the LGU;
Subsequently, use the Program of Works as a basis for allocating a budget for a project to avoid the process of re-appropriation;
Ensure consistency in the name of the projects in all its related documents;
The Municipal Accountant’s Office and the Municipal Engineer’s Office to coordinate regarding the discrepancy in the records of the OMA and actual cost of the project  per SWA so that it may already be recorded to its proper asset account;
The Municipal Budget Office to –
Ensure that any changes in the annual budget are duly supported with Supplemental Budget;
Ensure that the budget proposal for a project was already supported with Program of Works to ensure that the appropriation for the implementation thereof is sufficient;
The Municipal Engineer’s Office to –
Issue Certification that the timebook and payroll for JEV nos. 1-7 was for the Installation of LED Street Lights Along Municipal Road – Poblacion and not for the  Construction of Streetlight Pedestal and Installation of Poles, Lamp Units, and wirings at Barangay Libertad and Poblacion National Highways
Subsequently, ensure that the Project Name and Location are correct in the timebook and payroll as indicated in the Annual Budget and the Program of Works;
The Municipal Project Monitoring Committee to prepare the “List of Ongoing and for Implementation Projects” based on the actual projects it has monitored and inspected then compare the same with the projects enumerated in the Annual Budget.

Recommendation:
We recommended the following –
The HRMO and OMA to recalculate the wages of the job orders mentioned in item 2 above as their daily rates were incorrectly paid. The underpayment cannot be charged to the 2025 appropriation and the overpayment shall be refunded.
Instruct the Human Resource Management Office to:
Ensure that all Job Order appointments are signed by the Municipal Mayor even if the job orders are assigned in the Sangguniang Bayan Office;
Ensure that the daily rate paid is the same as the daily rate indicated in the job order;
Submit the lacking DTRs, Travel Orders and CA noted in this finding;
Subsequently, ensure that the payroll of job orders are completely supported with approved Daily Time Record, Travel Order or Request to Travel, and Certificate of Appearance.
The Management to instruct the Heads of Office to –
Limit the travel of the job orders only for (a) undertaking official missions/tasks which cannot be performed by/or assigned to other any regular/permanent official and/or employee of the agency, and/or (b) performing tasks/activities necessary to be able to fulfill the obligations as contained in his/her contract of service;
Ensure that the travel destination of the job order is clearly specified in the Travel Order or Request to Travel;
