Remit to GSIS all past due and unremitted premiums and loan payments withheld from City employees in full and within the required period to avoid interests and penalties that the GSIS may impose;
Conduct further analysis and retrieval of necessary supporting documents to establish the final balances of the SLs to correct the negative balances in the books, particularly those improperly recorded remittances and long outstanding balances resulting from data migration;
Reconcile their records every month to promptly establish the actual amount withheld from employees for immediate recording and remittance to the GSIS; and
HRMD to:
Regularly coordinate with CAD on the Due to GSIS account reconciliation to address the root cause and mitigate the 
under-remittances of withheld premiums and loan contributions for each employee.

We recommended that the Municipal Accountant:
locate available records/documents to determine the source agency and corresponding amount of fund transfers from NGAs of the unknown balances;
immediately effect the correction of the erroneously posted amount of fiesta fund for fair presentation of financial statements;
maintain Subsidiary Ledgers for the Due to NGAs Account; and
comply with the provision of Section 2 and 111 of P.D. No. 1445.

We recommended management to:
conduct a review of the purposes for which funds were transferred to ensure compliance with memorandum of agreement or other documents prescribing their proper and timely utilization;
identify and analyze the root causes of delays in project implementation through a comprehensive review of plans and applicable processes;
establish monitoring mechanisms to track the utilization of transferred funds and ensure compliance with intended purposes; and
If warranted, request from the source agency the authority to utilize funds for other purposes by providing proper justifications to support its necessity; otherwise, the unutilized amounts should be returned to fully liquidate the transferred funds.

We recommended to Management the following:
the Municipal Accountant to maintain Subsidiary Ledgers for breeding Stocks and Work/Zoo Animals;
the Municipal Accountant and the Municipal Agriculturist to trace and update their records of the breeding Stocks and Work/Zoo Animals to determine its composition and costs;
the Municipal Agriculturist to determine the cause of death of the animals and secure necessary documents to file relief from property accountability, if any, or to exact accountability from persons liable;
the General Services Officer and Municipal Agriculturist to reconcile and consolidate their inventory reports and reconcile the same to the accounting unit; and
Work back and determine the nature of these breeding animals if it really belongs to the LGU and if determined to be for the beneficiary-farmers as part of the livelihood program of the government thru the Department of Agriculture, transfer the ownership thereof to the beneficiaries and derecognize the recorded value in the books of the Municipality consistent with the issued COA Circular on one-time cleansing.

We recommended:
the Local Chief Executive to enforce the settlement of the above audit disallowances which have become final and executory and in compliance with COA Circular No. 2009-006;
the Municipal Accountant to disclose in the Notes to Financial Statements the disallowances which have not yet become final and executory;
the Municipal Accountant to review previous records which served as the bases of Accounting Office in recording Receivables-Disallowances in order to determine the persons liable and other details necessary in the monitoring of receivables; and
the Municipal Treasurer to immediately notify the Audit Team regarding settlement of disallowances and submit proof of settlement thereof for prompt issuance of NSSDC, or in the alternative, submit a monthly summary of settlement of disallowances.

We recommended that:
the management continuously require all Departments/End-Users/Implementing Offices to prepare and submit their respective PPMPs using the prescribed format and within the designated deadline, as per Section 318 of R.A. No. 7160, to facilitate timely preparation and approval of the Municipality's Indicative APP for CY 2023;
the BAC Secretariat, based on the submitted and reviewed PPMPs, prepare the APP in the form prescribed by the GPPB, indicating therein among others, the mode of procurement to be adopted, schedule for each procurement activities, and contract implementation to ensure that its procurement activities are properly/adequately planned;
the management meticulously and judiciously plan the procurement methods and timelines for each procurement activity and contract implementation, as mandated by Section 7 of the 2016 Revised IRR of R.A. No. 9184, to enhance the efficiency and effectiveness of the procurement process;
the management provide training and capacity-building programs for relevant personnel involved in the preparation of PPMPs and APP to ensure a thorough understanding of the requirements and guidelines set out in the 2016 Revised IRR of R.A. No. 9184 and other applicable laws; and
the management establish a monitoring and evaluation mechanism to oversee the preparation and submission of PPMPs and APP, ensuring compliance with the stipulated timelines and guidelines, and addressing any deficiencies promptly.

We recommended Management to:
Direct the Municipal Engineer and the BAC Secretariat to submit the lacking documents needed by the Technical Audit Team to facilitate the inspection of the projects;
Direct the Municipal Engineer to submit the required Statement of Work Accomplished upon expiry of contract for computation of Liquidated Damages in compliance to Republic Act No. 9184;
Direct the Municipal Engineer to promptly request the contractor to repair the identified defects, imposing applicable sanctions and penalties if deemed necessary;
Provide a compliance report on the actions taken to address the recommendations outlined in the Technical Inspection Report once rectification is completed; and
Enhance monitoring efforts on all ongoing and recently completed projects to reduce defects and prevent any deficiencies from arising.

We recommended that Management:
require the BAC/BAC Secretariat to immediately submit the lacking documents. Otherwise, we will be constrained to issue a Notice of Suspension pursuant to COA rules and regulations.
To ensure that all lacking documents are submitted, we urge the responsible personnel to accomplish the attached checklist of documentary requirements and to put index tabs/tabbings on the documents to be submitted.
Henceforth, we recommended Management, thru the Bids and Awards Committee, to ensure that all supporting contract documents are complete in compliance with pertinent provisions of R.A. No. 9184 and its IRR, and submitted within five (5) days from execution of contracts in accordance with Section 9.1 of COA Circular No. 2009-001 and COA Circular No. 2012-001;
reinforce the role of the BAC Secretariat by centralizing the preparation of procurement documents within it. This should help alleviate coordination issues and improve the management of document preparation;
allocate funds to support full-time staff positions within the BAC Secretariat as prescribed by the Guidelines on Establishing Procurement Systems and Organizations. This step is critical to providing the necessary administrative support and ensuring timely and efficient procurement processes;
re-evaluate the designation of procurement-related personnel of the municipality to avoid over-assignment of duties and responsibilities for them to effectively and efficiently perform the task assigned to them. The head of the procuring entity shall consider procurement proficiency as a factor in designating the head of the Secretariat and Procurement Unit;
clearly define and schedule all procurement activities in the Annual Procurement Plan to ensure structured procurement activities, thereby reducing delays;
strictly enforce compliance with Section 14.3 of the 2016 Revised IRR of R.A. No. 9184, ensuring that all members of the BAC, its Secretariat, and TWG give utmost priority to their procurement assignments. Implement monitoring mechanisms to oversee and ensure the prioritization of these duties;
require the personnel in charge of procurement to undergo training programs which are conducted, authorized, or accredited by the Government Procurement Policy Board (GPPB) and its Technical Support Office. Set a compliance monitoring system to verify completion of these trainings within six months from the date of designation;
harmonize the functions and responsibilities of the TWG as outlined in Executive Order No. 26 and the Guidelines on Procurement Systems and Organizations. Clearly define and communicate these roles to avoid confusion and inefficiency in the procurement process; and
schedule regular monitoring on compliance with procurement laws and guidelines. Establish a feedback mechanism where issues can be reported and addressed promptly to prevent the recurrence of similar problems.

We recommended that management:
strictly require the procuring office to observe the provisions of R.A. No. 9184, its Revised IRR and GPPB issuances to avoid violation thereof;
instruct the Bids and Awards Committee and the BAC Secretariat to be meticulous and judicious in the preparation of the Annual Procurement Plan which serves as the guide of the LGU in the timing of procurement and in the determination of the proper procurement modality. Scheduling of procurement activities should be done in such a manner that the BAC and the other offices/units in the Procuring Entity that are involved in the procurement process are able to efficiently manage the conduct of procurement transactions. Moreover, it is paramount that project implementation timelines are met;
ensure that procurements which can be embraced in one contract should be captured in one procurement plan and should not be split into artificial phases in compliance to COA Circular No. 76-41; and
empower the BAC/BAC Secretariat by providing them staff support in order to ensure that all their tasks are done efficiently, effectively, complete and compliant with laws, rules and regulations on procurement.

We recommended that management:
submit a written justification why they opted to conduct their activities outside the Province and the necessity why they included a large number of participants;
refrain from conducting activities using government resources outside the Municipality or Province if it is not required or necessary;
conduct cost and benefit analysis in conducting activities outside the Municipality or Province and these must be judiciously planned to ensure the appropriate utilization of government resources; and
must exercise prudence in the utilization of the funds of the Municipality and in an economical, efficient and effective manner that is essential and beneficial to the best interest of the constituents and not of chosen few only.

Based on the identified deficiencies and to address the recurring issues, we recommended and the Local Chief Executive agreed to:
Regularly check and update the Inventory Committee membership to make sure that all members are active in service and adjust the composition as needed to maintain an effective oversight team;
Instruct the Inventory Committee to (i) conduct actual physical count of all PPE of the Municipality on or before January 31 of each year; (ii) reconcile the inventory reports with the accounting records; and (iii) promptly submit the related RPCPPE to the Audit Team;
Ensure that the Property Officer maintain property cards, to effectively oversee and manage the agency's properties; and
Task the Inventory Committee in prioritizing the one-time cleansing of PPE account balances as per COA Circular No. 2020-006 to address historical reliability issues in financial statements. Allocate dedicated time and resources, including relieving the inventory committee of regular duties, to conduct thorough inventory verification and reconciliation activities on PPE accounts.

We recommended and the Local Chief Executive agreed to instruct the
implementing Offices to continue adhering with the guidelines and requirements on the efficient utilization of funds received from the NGAs for implementation of various programs, projects, and activities;
(b) 	Municipal Accountant to exert best efforts to review and trace the pertinent documents on the subject transactions particularly non-moving old account balances and effect the necessary adjustments/corrections, as warranted, to reflect the correct balances of Due to NGAs and other affected accounts in the books of the Municipality;
(c) 	responsible officer/s to coordinate with the Source Agencies (SAs) of the funds for actions to be taken on the unutilized balances and/or cause the immediate return of the balances, if warranted.

We recommended and the LCE agreed to strictly comply with the provisions of RA No. 9003 by:
(a) 	prioritizing the procurement of dump trucks for hauling of wastes in all barangays of the Municipality, and establishment of final disposal facility;
(b) 	requiring the OIC-MENRO to take appropriate action on the donated machineries to be operational;
(c) 	implementing waste diversion strategies in order to reduce waste at source;
(d) 	strengthening the role of the barangays in solid waste management and adopt the strategies mentioned in the SWMP at barangay level; and
(e) 	rigorous implementation of the Municipal Ordinances in relation to SWM and impose sanctions to violators, if warranted.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor require the MT to:
a. Compel the preparation of the RCDs pursuant to the provisions set forth in Section 49 of MNGAS for LGUs, Volume II and;
b. Provide the Collecting Officers a separate cashbook in accordance with Items a, b, and c of Section 181 of GAAM, Volume I.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor:
For those PPEs with issued PAR:
a. Instruct the Designated Property Custodian to prepare demand letters addressed to each concerned Accountable Officer (AO)/Personnel to produce the PPE he/she is accountable for to those PPEs with issued PAR; and
b. Instruct the Municipal Accountant to set up the corresponding receivables from concerned AOs/Personnels for the non-existing/missing PPEs that could not be produced upon demand, if any, the amount of which shall be based on depreciated replacement cost, which is replacement cost (current market price) less accumulated depreciation calculated based on replacement cost;
For those PPEs without issued PAR:
c. Cause the conduct of an investigation to determine the last known location/office where the missing PPE items were issued/installed, person accountable, circumstances of the loss, and the persons responsible for the loss, among others;
d. If accountability/responsibility over the missing PPE was pinpointed after investigation, instruct the Designated Property Custodian to demand from the accountable personnel to produce the item or pay the depreciated replacement cost;
e. Furnish the Municipal Accountant with the certified copy of the investigation report and demand letter to be used as basis to recognize loss of PPE and to set up the corresponding receivables from the concerned AO/Personnel; and
f. lf accountability/responsibility over the missing PPE could not be pinpointed after investigation, request for authority for derecognition thereof from the books of accounts from this Commission, in accordance with Paragraph 8 of Circular No. 2020-006.
Henceforth, ensure that the RPCPPE, accounting and property records are reconciled as at year end.

We recommended the following:
The PSMD to submit to the MACCO the Inventory Report of Vehicles/Heavy Equipment as of December 31, 2023 and every year thereafter;
The MACCO and the GSO to –
Reconcile the accounting records with the inventory report starting calendar year 2023 and every year thereafter;
Once the unrecorded machinery and transportation equipment are identified, coordinate for the retrieval of documents in order that the correct cost is recorded in the books of the LGU;
The Municipal Accountant Office to make the necessary journal entries to correct the balances of the affected accounts and submit the same together with working papers and supporting documents;
The Management to undertake the one-time cleansing of the Municipality’s “Machinery and Equipment” and “Transportation Equipment” accounts by following the guidelines set forth under COA Circular 2020-006 in order that the PPE account of the LGU becomes reliable and verifiable.

We recommended to the Municipal Accountant to –
Revert to the unappropriated surplus of the General Fund the accounts payable that is already outstanding for more than two years;
Ensure that transactions recorded as accounts payable are completely supported with the required documents and the same be under the custody of the office for safekeeping and must be readily available for review and verification upon request by the auditor.

We recommended to the management instruct the BAC to do the following:
Refrain from accepting alternate documentary requirements pursuant to GPPB Resolution No. 09-2020 unless a State of Calamity, or implementation of community quarantine or similar restrictions has been declared or being implemented;
Require the concerned contractors to post additional performance security covering the periods and amounts which were not covered in the original performance security and submit a copy of the same to the COA Auditor for review;
Carefully review the tenor, amounts, and validity period of ensuing performance securities; and
Implement proper sanctions on erring bidders and follow the prescribed procedures in case of defaults.

We recommended to the management to do the following:
Conduct an investigation as to the propriety of the acts of the concerned LGU officials and impose necessary sanctions if found improper;
Assess the validity of the subsequent four (4) contracts and implement proper actions;
Assess the reason for the delay of implementation of the four (4) projects and impose liquidated damages against the erring contractors if found at fault; and
Follow the guidelines for the proper grounds and procedures in terminating government contracts.

We recommended to the management to instruct the BAC and BAC Secretariat to do the following:
Submit the herein-identified lacking supporting documents to the contract;
Diligently follow the procurement procedures as prescribed by law, rules and regulations, and other relevant issuances;
Carefully and thoroughly check the information, tenor, terms and conditions contained in the Bidding Documents before approving and distributing the same to the prospective bidders; and
Carefully and thoroughly evaluate the Bidding Documents submitted by the prospective bidders, otherwise, contracts executed by the LGU with the winning bidders who submitted Bidding Documents (Legal, Technical, and Financial Aspects) with errors, deficiencies and misrepresentations may be declared void and without effect;
Impose proper sanctions on non-compliant bids, otherwise, the BAC may be held liable for passing a deficient bid.

We recommended the following:
The Management to –
Look for guidelines (legal opinions, cases, law) which may be used to ratify (if allowed)  the contract entered into without a valid appropriation;
Ensure that an Appropriation Ordinance covering the Supplemental Budget is already enacted before payment is made to the supplier of the Extrication Rescue Equipment.
Municipal Budget Officer to –
Coordinate with the LDRRMO for the identification of the discontinued expenditure items in the original LDRRMF budget in order to prepare the Supplemental Budget;
Ensure, that an Appropriation Ordinance is already enacted before certifying that there is an available appropriation for the disbursement;
Henceforth, ensure that there is an Appropriation Ordinance covering any changes in the Annual Budget especially if the changes are reappropriation from one expense class to another.

We recommended the following –
The Property and Supply Management Division to:
Trace the reported vehicles with existing ARE/PAR but were not found during inspection (Item Nos. 29,34,36, and 47);
Trace the six (6) unreported vehicles but with existing ARE. If those were truly given to the six barangays of the Municipality, inspect the same and prepare the necessary documents for its transfer;
Issue Property Acknowledgement Receipts for the 19 remaining serviceable vehicles without PAR and ensure that the PARs are properly filled-up;
Renew all existing ARE/PAR of the vehicles and ensure that the newly issued PARs are properly filled-up;
Cancel all the ARE/PAR for unserviceable vehicles;
Henceforth,
Keep intact and complete records of the PARs, Property Return Slip, and other documents relative to the ownership and transfer of the vehicles;
Ensure that the PARs are renewed every three years or every time there is a change in custodianship/user of the property.
The Management to:
Instruct the heads of office to properly return all unserviceable properties to the PMSD by preparing the Property Return Slip;
Instruct the MISS to coordinate with the PSMD for the preparation of the inventory sticker of the vehicles;
Ensure that the unserviceable properties are placed in a secure location to avoid loss of the property.

Immediately restitute the cash shortage;

Stop the unsound practices of handling cash; and

Comply with the aforementioned provisions of P.D. No. 1445.

expedite the implementation of all on – going programmed and funded projects under the 20% DF to optimize utilization thereof and to ensure timely delivery of intended benefits for the constituents of the municipality;

continuously ensure that the development projects that may be included under the 20% DF shall be those that are necessary, appropriate, or incidental to efficient and effective local governance, and those which are essential to the promotion of the general welfare of the people; and

ensure that the development projects to be funded out of the 20% DF are well-planned and procurement-and-implementation-ready.

continuously ensure the allocation and utilization of LDRRMF pursuant to the policies and guidelines primarily embodied in NDRRMC-DBM-DILG Joint Memorandum Circular No. 2013-1;

ensure efficient and effective implementation of all programmed projects identified during the budget year to optimize the utilization of the fund and to assure that the goals and objectives of reducing disaster risk and enhancing disaster preparedness and response capabilities be achieved; and

continuously comply with pertinent laws, rules and regulations in the recording, utilization and reporting of LDRRMF.

consider hiring additional personnel for the Accounting Office since the preparation of most of reports are delegated only to one personnel. 
the Municipal Accountant and Municipal Budget Officer to reconcile the balances of their report; 

the Municipal Accountant to maintain Subsidiary Ledgers to support the balance presented in the financial statements;

