We recommended to the Local Chief Executive to submit a valid justification on the incurrence of delays in the completion of projects undertaken thru straight contract without imposing liquidated damages and other sanctions applicable against erring contractors.

Specifically, the following procedures available for management should be resorted: 

Impose the collection of these unliquidated damages from identified contractors in default; 

Require the Municipal Accountant to, henceforth, compute for liquidated damages and deduct the same from the progress/final billings of the contractor with a corresponding brief explanation on the face of the disbursement voucher, if negative slippage occurs;

Implement effective monitoring and evaluation control on the status of implementation of infrastructure projects to at least prevent negative slippage;

When the total sum of liquidated damages reached the ten percent (10%) of the total contract price, initiate the appropriate actions pursuant to above-mentioned Section 9.4, Annex E of the revised IRR of RA No. 9184;

Remind contractors to complete their projects on or before the end of contract duration. For those with pending works and a negative slippage has been incurred already, demand the contractors to hastily complete the project and issue negative slippage warnings pursuant to GPPB Circular No. 03-2019 dated March 8, 2019, without prejudice to the imposition of liquidated damages until the works have been completed;

If the delayed projects will not be continued by the contractors or if at least 15% negative slippage occurs, adopt termination of contract and forfeiture of performance security. After termination, take over the contract or resort to any of other alternative methods of procurement provided under RA No. 9184 and its 2016 revised IRR. Thereafter, issue a blacklisting order to sanction the erring contractors in order to prohibit the latter to participate in the bidding of any government projects/contracts;

Require the contractors to submit SWA to Municipal Engineering Office (MEO) at the expiration of the contract duration; and

The MEO to review meticulously the SWA prepared by the contractors as to completeness of the required details and that contract duration should be consistent among the documents submitted, more particularly the Program of Works, Inspection Report.

